<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910719-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>910719-0020.</DOCID><HL>   Bert Lance Ordered   To Pay $2.7 Million   To FDIC for Loans</HL><DATE>07/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A federal court ordered Bert Lance,President Carter's budget director, to pay the FederalDeposit Insurance Corp. $2.7 million to cover defaulted bankloans.   Mr. Lance consented to the judgment to settle a 1989 FDICsuit charging that he and a defunct personal holding companyhad defaulted on four loans from the United American Bank ofKnoxville, Tenn. The FDIC assumed the loans after it closedthe bank in 1983. In its suit the FDIC charged that Mr. Lancehad failed to comply with a 1986 agreement to repay theloans.</LP><TEXT>   The consent order, issued by a federal district court inRome, Ga., requires Mr. Lance to pay the FDIC $1.3 million inprincipal, $1.3 million in interest and $63,000 in attorney'sfees to cover the cost of the agency's action against him.   Neither Mr. Lance nor his attorney could be reached forcomment.   Mr. Lance, who became federal budget director in 1977,served for eight months before resigning in the face ofallegations that he had made questionable loans to friendsand relatives while a banker in Georgia.</TEXT></DOC>